Here is a simple JavaScript program that allows users to draw on an HTML5 canvas:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <title>Canvas Drawing</title>
    <style>
        #canvas {
            border: 1px solid black;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <canvas id="canvas" width="800" height="600"></canvas>
    <script>
        let canvas = document.getElementById('canvas');
        let ctx = canvas.getContext('2d');
        let drawing = false;
        let lastX, lastY;

        canvas.addEventListener('mousedown', (e) => {
            drawing = true;
            lastX = e.offsetX;
            lastY = e.offsetY;
        });

        canvas.addEventListener('mousemove', (e) => {
            if (drawing) {
                ctx.beginPath();
                ctx.moveTo(lastX, lastY);
                ctx.lineTo(e.offsetX, e.offsetY);
                ctx.stroke();
                lastX = e.offsetX;
                lastY = e.offsetY;
            }
        });

        canvas.addEventListener('mouseup', () => {
            drawing = false;
        });

        canvas.addEventListener('mouseout', () => {
            drawing = false;
        });
    </script>
</body>
</html>
```

This program creates a canvas element and gets a reference to it using `document.getElementById('canvas')`. It then gets a 2D drawing context using `canvas.getContext('2d')`.

The program then sets up event listeners for the `mousedown`, `mousemove`, `mouseup`, and `mouseout` events on the canvas. When the user clicks and drags the mouse, the program draws a line on the canvas from the previous mouse position to the current mouse position. When the user releases the mouse button, the program stops drawing.

The `lastX` and `lastY` variables keep track of the previous mouse position, and the `drawing` variable keeps track of whether the user is currently drawing.

